1
00:01:58,095 --> 00:02:00,370
Quit eyeballing me, Flavius.

2
00:02:00,615 --> 00:02:03,687
I knew you when you was
a two-bit hustler on Bull Street.

3
00:02:48,895 --> 00:02:51,045
Excuse me!
Where can a fella get a cab?

4
00:02:51,295 --> 00:02:52,284
He just left.

5
00:02:52,535 --> 00:02:55,049
You can call the company, but I's you,
I'd wait on him to come back.

6
00:02:55,295 --> 00:02:56,933
'Less you want to take a ride.

7
00:02:57,175 --> 00:02:59,052
- You going to Jones Street?
- I'll get you there.

8
00:02:59,775 --> 00:03:01,049
Put your stuff in there.

9
00:03:06,055 --> 00:03:08,410
<i>To your right, Pirate's House...</i>

10
00:03:08,655 --> 00:03:10,930
<i>... built in 1794.</i>

11
00:03:11,175 --> 00:03:14,963
<i>All the ne'er-do-wells and scalawags</i>
<i>divided up their booty there.</i>

12
00:03:16,695 --> 00:03:18,890
<i>Sherman stayed</i>
<i>in the Green-Meldrim House...</i>

13
00:03:19,135 --> 00:03:21,933
<i>... to rest up</i>
<i>after his fiery march through Atlanta.</i>

14
00:03:22,175 --> 00:03:23,813
<i>He was going to burn Savannah...</i>

15
00:03:24,055 --> 00:03:27,047
<i>... but the locals drowned him</i>
<i>in Chatham Artillery punch...</i>

16
00:03:27,295 --> 00:03:29,604
<i>... and fancy parties</i>
<i>till he decided...</i>

17
00:03:29,855 --> 00:03:31,686
<i>... to spare our fair city.</i>

18
00:03:31,935 --> 00:03:34,165
<i>Forsyth Park, ladies and gentlemen.</i>

19
00:03:58,935 --> 00:04:00,368
You looking for something?

20
00:04:02,255 --> 00:04:03,210
No.

21
00:04:26,015 --> 00:04:27,130
Mr. Kelso?

22
00:04:27,375 --> 00:04:29,206
Are you Mr. Kelso?

23
00:04:29,535 --> 00:04:32,811
I'm Lorene Baxter.
Welcome to Savannah.

24
00:04:33,535 --> 00:04:36,732
<i>Town & Country</i>
is my favorite magazine.

25
00:04:37,255 --> 00:04:41,009
Oh, my land, where are my manners?
What can I get you to drink?

26
00:04:41,975 --> 00:04:43,693
Anything cold would be great.

27
00:04:49,735 --> 00:04:51,885
Mr. Williams restored this home.

28
00:04:52,135 --> 00:04:54,933
One of the many he saved
from the wrecking ball.

29
00:04:57,415 --> 00:05:00,134
The carriage house is reserved
for Jim's clients...

30
00:05:00,375 --> 00:05:02,809
...and guests, such as yourself.

31
00:05:13,095 --> 00:05:14,289
He's here.

32
00:05:17,095 --> 00:05:19,404
Welcome, Mr. Kelsy.

33
00:05:19,735 --> 00:05:22,488
- I'm sorry, Mr. Kelso?
- John Kelso.

34
00:05:22,735 --> 00:05:24,566
Yes. I'm Betty Harty.

35
00:05:24,815 --> 00:05:26,328
Sonny's been expecting you.

36
00:05:26,575 --> 00:05:28,486
I'm here to see Jim Williams.

37
00:05:28,735 --> 00:05:30,612
Sonny's Jim's attorney.

38
00:05:34,895 --> 00:05:36,169
Well, hell...

39
00:05:36,415 --> 00:05:37,734
...come on in, coach.

40
00:05:38,335 --> 00:05:39,290
John Kelso.

41
00:05:40,415 --> 00:05:43,452
Welcome to the old curiosity shop.
Take a seat.

42
00:05:51,815 --> 00:05:53,726
You let me know.

43
00:05:56,655 --> 00:05:58,850
- How was your trip?
- Fine. Mr. Williams said...

44
00:05:59,095 --> 00:06:03,054
He will be right along. We have
a little business to attend to first.

45
00:06:03,295 --> 00:06:06,765
Confidentiality agreement.
Just boilerplate stuff.

46
00:06:07,015 --> 00:06:08,334
Plus a paragraph...

47
00:06:08,615 --> 00:06:11,493
...outlining Jim's editorial privileges.

48
00:06:12,935 --> 00:06:17,087
<i>Town & Country</i> flew me down to write
a 500-word story on a Christmas party.

49
00:06:17,335 --> 00:06:19,929
It's a literary postcard.
Are you serious about this?

50
00:06:20,495 --> 00:06:22,167
It's not just any party.

51
00:06:24,175 --> 00:06:25,688
Have you asked the magazine?

52
00:06:25,935 --> 00:06:28,768
I'd rather have your word
than some New York lawyer.

53
00:06:30,495 --> 00:06:32,213
Be that as it may...

54
00:06:33,015 --> 00:06:34,733
...I'm not going to sign that.

55
00:06:35,935 --> 00:06:37,573
Damn! How come?

56
00:06:38,335 --> 00:06:40,246
It's just a little old party write-up.

57
00:06:40,695 --> 00:06:42,811
All the more reason
not to compromise my ethics.

58
00:06:43,055 --> 00:06:45,853
As a professional,
I'm sure you understand.

59
00:06:50,895 --> 00:06:52,294
Promise to be fair?

60
00:06:52,815 --> 00:06:54,533
Yes, of course.

61
00:07:02,735 --> 00:07:03,645
Jim...

62
00:07:05,135 --> 00:07:06,853
...this is John Kelso.

63
00:07:07,135 --> 00:07:08,170
Hello.

64
00:07:09,855 --> 00:07:11,925
Let's take a walk,
shall we, sport?

65
00:07:15,935 --> 00:07:18,085
We'll go around Forsyth Park.

66
00:07:29,375 --> 00:07:30,649
Would y'all mind...?

67
00:07:30,895 --> 00:07:32,533
Not at all, Betty.

68
00:07:33,575 --> 00:07:34,530
Come on.

69
00:07:41,775 --> 00:07:43,333
Did you sign Sonny's papers?

70
00:07:43,655 --> 00:07:44,770
Actually, no.

71
00:07:45,935 --> 00:07:49,894
Good for you. Sonny's
overly protective of my interests.

72
00:07:50,495 --> 00:07:52,645
- Still walking the dog, Mr. Glover?
- Yes, sir.

73
00:07:52,895 --> 00:07:55,250
Patrick do love his morning walk.

74
00:08:00,775 --> 00:08:03,847
Would you mind? Could I please have
my picture made with Uga?

75
00:08:04,255 --> 00:08:05,210
Great.

76
00:08:05,495 --> 00:08:06,530
Thanks.

77
00:08:08,335 --> 00:08:10,007
All right. Smile.

78
00:08:12,215 --> 00:08:13,933
Thanks. Dang good dog.

79
00:08:15,495 --> 00:08:16,405
Thank you very much.

80
00:08:16,695 --> 00:08:17,923
Thank you for asking.

81
00:08:19,375 --> 00:08:22,333
No matter what you and I ever do
in our lives, Mr. Kelso...

82
00:08:22,615 --> 00:08:24,731
...neither of us
will be as famous as Uga.

83
00:08:25,535 --> 00:08:26,604
He's the university mascot.

84
00:08:26,855 --> 00:08:28,686
- "The Georgia Bulldog."
- Is that right?

85
00:08:29,015 --> 00:08:32,928
I know I'm going to regret asking,
but that man said he was walking a dog.

86
00:08:34,815 --> 00:08:35,850
What dog?

87
00:08:36,135 --> 00:08:38,285
Mr. Glover was the law firm porter.

88
00:08:38,735 --> 00:08:42,853
Mr. Bouhan said in his will that
Mr. Glover should continue to be paid...

89
00:08:43,135 --> 00:08:46,252
...$ 15 every week for walking Patrick,
his Labrador.

90
00:08:46,575 --> 00:08:47,610
So...

91
00:08:48,455 --> 00:08:49,444
...where's Patrick?

92
00:08:49,735 --> 00:08:54,365
Patrick went on to his great rewards
2 years after Mr. Bouhan, about 1974.

93
00:08:54,655 --> 00:08:56,532
- The dog's dead.
- Quite.

94
00:08:57,615 --> 00:08:59,765
Why doesn't Mr. Glover walk Uga?

95
00:09:02,735 --> 00:09:04,612
Well, then, who'd walk Patrick?

96
00:09:08,295 --> 00:09:09,694
I see.

97
00:09:12,215 --> 00:09:14,171
- There it is.
- This is your house?

98
00:09:14,975 --> 00:09:18,934
Built by General Hugh Mercer in 1860,
but he never lived in this house.

99
00:09:19,215 --> 00:09:21,171
His great-grandson was Johnny Mercer.

100
00:09:21,455 --> 00:09:22,524
The songwriter?

101
00:09:22,815 --> 00:09:24,043
Savannah's own.

102
00:09:24,855 --> 00:09:26,686
What's your favorite of his tunes?

103
00:09:27,375 --> 00:09:30,253
My mother was always partial
to "Fools Rush In."

104
00:09:30,655 --> 00:09:31,804
Your mother.

105
00:09:32,615 --> 00:09:33,491
Indeed.

106
00:09:33,895 --> 00:09:38,685
I'd love to give you the grand tour, but
they're still setting up for the party.

107
00:09:39,615 --> 00:09:41,446
I thought the party was tomorrow night.

108
00:09:41,735 --> 00:09:43,214
There are two parties.

109
00:09:43,455 --> 00:09:46,413
Tonight is for bachelors.
Gentlemen only.

110
00:09:47,575 --> 00:09:48,690
Would you like to come?

111
00:09:49,855 --> 00:09:50,890
I'd like to cover it.

112
00:09:51,135 --> 00:09:54,286
I'm sorry. It's private.
Reporters aren't allowed.

113
00:09:54,535 --> 00:09:57,527
Would you like to see my shop?
It's back here in the carriage house.

114
00:10:00,015 --> 00:10:04,691
This house is one of the largest
in Savannah. It covers an entire block.

115
00:10:04,975 --> 00:10:06,328
It's right in here.

116
00:10:06,615 --> 00:10:08,446
This is where we do all of our...

117
00:10:08,695 --> 00:10:10,174
...restorations.

118
00:10:21,735 --> 00:10:23,566
This landscape, is it a Stubbs?

119
00:10:24,255 --> 00:10:25,404
Very good.

120
00:10:26,015 --> 00:10:27,448
My father was a dealer.

121
00:10:27,695 --> 00:10:30,732
It's called <i>Newmarket Heath</i>
<i>with a Rubbing-Down House.</i>

122
00:10:30,975 --> 00:10:33,648
It's a recent purchase I will unveil
at tomorrow night's event.

123
00:10:34,055 --> 00:10:35,568
It's an odd piece.

124
00:10:36,175 --> 00:10:37,893
The impasto is interesting.

125
00:10:38,935 --> 00:10:40,004
Where's your black light?

126
00:10:49,815 --> 00:10:50,770
It's an overpaint.

127
00:10:51,575 --> 00:10:53,247
Very good, sport.

128
00:10:57,575 --> 00:10:59,566
- You had it x-rayed yet?
- No.

129
00:11:00,495 --> 00:11:02,247
How will you know
what it's obscuring?

130
00:11:04,055 --> 00:11:05,886
I rather enjoy not knowing.

131
00:12:02,015 --> 00:12:03,209
Just a minute.

132
00:12:11,055 --> 00:12:12,693
- Who is it?
- Mandy.

133
00:12:12,975 --> 00:12:13,851
Who?

134
00:12:15,735 --> 00:12:16,884
I don't know a Mandy.

135
00:12:17,135 --> 00:12:19,603
Of course not.
You won't open the damn door.

136
00:12:21,295 --> 00:12:23,172
Hi. Nice to meet you.

137
00:12:31,655 --> 00:12:33,566
You all got some ice?

138
00:12:35,855 --> 00:12:37,174
Sure, help yourself.

139
00:12:37,655 --> 00:12:40,727
Joe Odom's fridge is on the blink.
And plus, at present...

140
00:12:40,975 --> 00:12:43,045
...we don't have electricity.

141
00:12:44,975 --> 00:12:46,249
Thirsty?

142
00:12:47,295 --> 00:12:49,445
Me? No.
No, not really.

143
00:12:51,215 --> 00:12:55,208
If you're thirsty, a drink'll cure it.
If you're not, a drink'll prevent it.

144
00:12:55,495 --> 00:12:57,804
Prevention is better than a cure.

145
00:13:00,655 --> 00:13:02,611
Put on some pants, John Kelso.

146
00:13:05,135 --> 00:13:06,648
Sure, just let me get a pair.

147
00:13:09,455 --> 00:13:12,333
This is our newest addition
to the Odom House.

148
00:13:12,655 --> 00:13:15,965
As you see, Joe's been creative
with our electrical dilemma.

149
00:13:18,455 --> 00:13:22,084
I done this before
and I ain't never been killed yet.

150
00:13:22,335 --> 00:13:24,724
But there's a first time for everything.

151
00:13:32,135 --> 00:13:33,011
There we go!

152
00:13:33,255 --> 00:13:34,449
We got it!

153
00:13:35,655 --> 00:13:36,565
No problem.

154
00:13:37,015 --> 00:13:38,084
Joe Odom?

155
00:13:38,335 --> 00:13:39,563
The one, the only.

156
00:13:39,935 --> 00:13:41,288
Where's my libation?

157
00:13:41,575 --> 00:13:42,405
Hold these.

158
00:13:44,135 --> 00:13:46,330
To Savannah Electric and Power!

159
00:13:46,975 --> 00:13:49,284
And let's not forget our friends...

160
00:13:49,855 --> 00:13:50,765
...the...

161
00:13:51,215 --> 00:13:51,931
...whoever!

162
00:13:53,455 --> 00:13:55,764
Here's to you!
All right, inside.

163
00:13:56,775 --> 00:14:01,132
Honey, that's a tough job,
but you're talking to the lady. Hello!

164
00:14:02,175 --> 00:14:05,008
Have you met Mr. Kelso,
our newest addition to Savannah?

165
00:14:05,295 --> 00:14:06,614
Jerry Spence.

166
00:14:06,855 --> 00:14:08,573
- How are you?
- I'm charmed now.

167
00:14:08,855 --> 00:14:10,971
- How are you?
- I'm pretty good.

168
00:14:11,215 --> 00:14:13,331
- I wonder if he goes to my church?
- I wonder.

169
00:14:13,655 --> 00:14:14,644
Episcopalian.

170
00:14:14,895 --> 00:14:16,089
We'll find out.

171
00:14:16,335 --> 00:14:17,563
<i>Sanitation</i>

172
00:14:18,175 --> 00:14:20,735
<i>I see all night long</i>
<i>Hauling in great big cans</i>

173
00:14:23,015 --> 00:14:26,246
<i>I'm hoping one day soon</i>
<i>She'll let me be a Hefty man</i>

174
00:14:27,695 --> 00:14:30,084
<i>In the Dumpster</i>
<i>We'll be making love</i>

175
00:14:30,335 --> 00:14:32,485
<i>In the Dumpster</i>
<i>Beneath the stars above</i>

176
00:14:32,815 --> 00:14:35,170
<i>In the Dumpster</i>
<i>I smell paradise</i>

177
00:14:35,455 --> 00:14:37,286
<i>Don 't have to ask me twice</i>

178
00:14:37,575 --> 00:14:39,531
<i>It's all I'm thinking of</i>

179
00:14:39,775 --> 00:14:42,335
<i>Just me and that trash girl</i>
<i>Making that Dumpster love</i>

180
00:14:54,575 --> 00:14:55,451
Do you like that?

181
00:14:55,695 --> 00:14:56,844
Strong.

182
00:14:57,215 --> 00:14:59,888
Strong and good.
Chatham Artillery punch.

183
00:15:00,175 --> 00:15:01,130
What's in it?

184
00:15:01,375 --> 00:15:03,093
3 parts fruit, 7 parts liquor.

185
00:15:03,375 --> 00:15:05,331
Whatever's available on both counts.

186
00:15:05,655 --> 00:15:07,293
Great party. Great house.

187
00:15:08,335 --> 00:15:12,692
The fella that owns it is in Europe
for a year. Asked me to look in on it.

188
00:15:12,975 --> 00:15:14,294
Water the plants.

189
00:15:17,575 --> 00:15:18,371
Squatting?

190
00:15:19,735 --> 00:15:21,487
That's a vicious word.

191
00:15:21,815 --> 00:15:23,453
You're not a lawyer, are you?

192
00:15:25,135 --> 00:15:28,207
Good. They're the scum of the earth.
And I should know...

193
00:15:28,495 --> 00:15:31,055
...being an ex-barrister myself.

194
00:15:31,455 --> 00:15:32,410
Ex?

195
00:15:33,055 --> 00:15:36,206
Ceremoniously disbarred
not two years ago.

196
00:15:36,495 --> 00:15:38,372
Had a little accounting snafu.

197
00:15:38,975 --> 00:15:40,203
What do you do now?

198
00:15:40,455 --> 00:15:43,253
Me and Mandy,
we're going to open a piano bar.

199
00:15:43,575 --> 00:15:44,610
You already have one.

200
00:15:44,855 --> 00:15:46,334
Looks that way, doesn't it?

201
00:15:46,855 --> 00:15:49,005
Wait a minute. Hold the music.

202
00:15:49,295 --> 00:15:50,171
Look.

203
00:15:52,095 --> 00:15:53,323
Look at this.

204
00:15:53,655 --> 00:15:54,724
Jerry Spence.

205
00:15:55,895 --> 00:15:58,614
You have outdone yourself again.

206
00:15:58,855 --> 00:16:02,450
That is a coif definitely befitting
your stature as the future ex...

207
00:16:02,775 --> 00:16:04,174
...Mrs. Joe Odom.

208
00:16:04,895 --> 00:16:06,613
Keep dreaming, darling.

209
00:16:07,015 --> 00:16:08,209
You're in love.

210
00:16:11,815 --> 00:16:13,806
She is one beautiful woman.

211
00:16:14,175 --> 00:16:15,574
You two engaged?

212
00:16:16,775 --> 00:16:17,844
Not yet.

213
00:16:19,575 --> 00:16:22,647
It's getting late. I'm going to
hit the road. Nice meeting you.

214
00:16:22,895 --> 00:16:24,248
No, wait a minute.

215
00:16:25,135 --> 00:16:26,773
Joe's rule #2:

216
00:16:27,055 --> 00:16:31,048
If you have to leave a party,
you always take a traveler.

217
00:16:32,015 --> 00:16:34,404
I can live with that one.
Nice to meet you.

218
00:16:41,735 --> 00:16:42,724
Hey, there.

219
00:16:43,655 --> 00:16:46,169
Better to be on the edge of a party,
don't you think?

220
00:16:48,415 --> 00:16:49,689
Thanks for inviting me.

221
00:16:49,935 --> 00:16:50,970
Anytime.

222
00:16:51,215 --> 00:16:52,489
Every time.

223
00:16:58,895 --> 00:17:00,010
Earlier...

224
00:17:00,255 --> 00:17:01,574
...how'd you know my name?

225
00:17:01,855 --> 00:17:03,447
Welcome to Savannah.

226
00:17:11,215 --> 00:17:12,330
Mr. John Kelso?

227
00:17:14,415 --> 00:17:15,370
This is for you.

228
00:17:23,375 --> 00:17:26,685
<i>I'm not in. Leave a message</i>
<i>and I'll get back to you.</i>

229
00:17:46,815 --> 00:17:48,373
- Mr. Kelso?
- Yes.

230
00:17:48,615 --> 00:17:51,209
I'm Lucille Wright.
I cater Mr. Williams' parties.

231
00:17:51,455 --> 00:17:53,173
- Nice to meet you.
- He'll be down shortly.

232
00:17:53,415 --> 00:17:55,167
Would you like to see what we'll serve?

233
00:17:55,415 --> 00:17:56,609
Of course.

234
00:17:56,855 --> 00:17:57,924
Come in.

235
00:18:00,215 --> 00:18:02,490
Lots of fresh vegetables...

236
00:18:02,735 --> 00:18:04,293
...hot bread...

237
00:18:04,535 --> 00:18:05,934
...jumbo shrimp.

238
00:18:07,535 --> 00:18:10,129
Let's see.
This is smoked ham and turkey.

239
00:18:10,735 --> 00:18:11,451
Both.

240
00:18:11,695 --> 00:18:15,654
A big fruit platter.
And this is a wonderful crab dish.

241
00:18:15,895 --> 00:18:16,805
A bisque?

242
00:18:17,375 --> 00:18:18,125
Jeff Braswell.

243
00:18:19,735 --> 00:18:23,011
- I shoot Jim's parties.
- Let's get a shot of the whole spread.

244
00:18:23,255 --> 00:18:25,644
<i>Town & Country</i>
loves its pretty pictures.

245
00:18:26,135 --> 00:18:28,091
And pumpkin cornbread.

246
00:18:29,455 --> 00:18:33,004
Mr. Williams insists on
low-country cooking for his parties.

247
00:18:33,495 --> 00:18:36,293
Oh, you're going to have fun tonight.

248
00:18:36,535 --> 00:18:38,287
Indeed he is, Lucille.

249
00:18:39,415 --> 00:18:41,724
Good fit. 44 long.

250
00:18:45,335 --> 00:18:47,610
I have an eye for framing things.

251
00:18:49,935 --> 00:18:51,926
Welcome to Mercer House, Mr. Kelso.

252
00:18:52,855 --> 00:18:55,244
You have outdone yourself again
this year.

253
00:18:55,495 --> 00:18:56,974
